akers, that part is obvious, but I wish that they would state their own opinions more clearly,\u201d said Sepp\u00e4l\u00e4. \nNylund on the other hand would encourage politicians to smile more. \n\u201dPoliticians look so serious. A lot of my friends have the opinion that politicians are quite stuffy with no sense of humor.\u201d A step from schools to politics \nPoliticians will have a chance to hone their facial skills as a record number of students participate in this year\u2019s Parliamentary Youth day. A total of 154 schools will get the chance to send a student representative, as well as one journalism student and one club director. \n\u201dThe new curriculum promotes getting involved and being an influencer, and it shows,\u201d said Tiina Karhuvirta, senior advisor and Youth Parliament organizer at Development Centre Opinkirjo. \nAccording to Karhuvirta, in past years the relationship between schools and politicians has been at times an issue of wary caution, as some teachers still feel reluctant to invite their district MP to their classroom. \nHowever, this mindset is a dwindling notion as the younger generation of teachers approach the topic with progress in mind. \n\u201cI don\u2019t feel that old traumas hamper my job. Civics studies is such a fruitful subject when looking at the development of the real world,\u201d said Laura Parikka, civics teacher at Porolahti school. \nStory continues after photograph Mikael Mikkonen dreams of a politician and musician's career. Image: Kalevi Rytk\u00f6l\u00e4 / Yle A dream to meet Laura Huhtasaari and P\u00e4ivi R\u00e4s\u00e4nen \nCore values are at the centreof the political views of 16-year old Mikael Mikkonen . A student at Vesala upper secondary school, Mikkonen joined the parliamentary club as soon as it started up. \nMikkonen knows he is the school's odd bird because of his strong political opinions. \n\u201cConservative and Christian values are close to my heart. Home, religion, the mother country, and the 