nal costs had not been taken into account in calculations made by the Ministry of Finance. Hunting for cuts \nLeading the rebellion is Jan Vapaavuori, the National Coalition Party Mayor of Helsinki who has declared trenchant opposition to the reform advanced by the government coalition that includes his own party. Vapaavuori's power base is strong, with some 30,000 people voting for him in the last municipal elections, and his party includes other critics of the reform including liberal-minded MP Elina Lepom\u00e4ki . \nTheir critique is two-pronged. The new regional governments, which are dear to the rural Centre Party , have no tax-raising powers and therefore no incentive to reduce costs. Private providers, meanwhile, could be incentivised to cherry-pick young, healthy customers and leaver the older, sicker and more expensive patients for public providers to pick up. \nThe chunk of money cut from budgets in the Uusimaa region will be the most substantial due to its population of 1.6 million--nearly a third of the total population of Finland. \nMunicipal leaders interviewed by Yle estimate that of the 300-million-euro deficit that Uusimaa will face, Helsinki will have to cough up 100 million euros per year, Espoo 50 million, and Vantaa 40 million euros. The remainder would be left for the rest of Uusimaa to come up with. \n\u201dThe equivalent to losing 100 million euros per year in Helsinki would be giving up the entirety of child protection services. That gives you an idea of the scale that we are talking about,\u201d says Helsinki deputy mayor Hanna Vesikansa. \nAccording to the Helsinki-Uusimaa Regional Council, the financial deficit would decrease over time, but not by much. In 2030 the deficit would still be 100 million euros for the entire Uusimaa region. Baby steps \nThe Helsinki-Uusimaa Regional Council have agreed with government officials that weekly negotiations will be held to thrash out funding issues. In addition, the leaders of the Helsinki Metropolitan Area said the transition should be carried out with patience and in baby steps. \n\u201dThis should be done in the same manner as the primary education reform was done back in the day. Start from small provinces and proceed step by step,\u201d said Ritva Viljanen, mayor of Vantaa. Sources", "highlightText": "", "highlightTitle": "", "language": "english", "external_links": [], "entities": {"persons": [{"name": "juha metso", "sentiment": "none"}, {"name": "markus syrj\u00e4inen", "sentiment": "none"}, {"name": "antti kolppo", "sentiment": "none"}], "organizations": [{"name": "yle  municipal", "sentiment": "none"}, {"name": "finance and administration", "sentiment": "none"}], "locations": [{"name": "espoo", "sentiment": "none"}, {"name": "finland", "sentiment": "none"}, {"name": "uusimaa", "sentiment": "none"}, {"name": "vantaa", "sentiment": "none"}, {"name": "helsinki", "sentiment": "none"}]}, "rating": null, "crawled": "2018-03-24T00:12:46.001+03:00"}, {"thread": {"uuid": "f8ef2f6a44ac447dc257d419198a03665f2ad6cb", "url": "http://omgili.com/ri/.wHSUbtEfZRInRBPslGLIkgfGNwDsjksPAxvVmaN.ncLu760umCDPDonhZFuKjVtEiilOvjDcdvS6sdAQxrrfOqseqgSAb.wPr6rZTCsueVfHe8_coHA_wspcYuaTmxQ_n6vSXwBJ1d9wD9_iCjAiA--", "site_full": "yle.fi", "site": "yle.fi", "site_section": "http://yle.fi/uutiset/rss/uutiset.rss?osasto=news", "site_categories": ["media"], "section_title": "Yle News | Tuoreimmat uutiset", "title": "Parliament rejects citizens\u2019 initiative to preserve Malmi airport", "title_full": "Parliament rejects citizens\u2019 initiative to preserve Malmi airport", "published": "2018-03-23T19:07:00.000+03:00", "replies_count": 0, "participants_count": 0, "site_type": "news", "country": "FI", "spam_score": 0.0, "main_image": "https://img.yle.fi/uutiset/kotimaa/article9537440.ece/ALTERNATES/w940h529/malmi%20Malmin%20lentoasema%20lentokentt%C3%A4%20DSC_0791.jpg", "performance_score": 0, "domain_rank": 2555, "social": {"facebook": {"likes": 41, "comments": 0, "shares": 41}, "gpl